John Deanwrites:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Mrs Dawson developed a disease caused by asbestos from a crumbling
&gt; fire safety curtain, an inquest was told.
">

Those safety devices'll get you every time.

Earlier this year ago I was on vacation with my father, who has
limited vision, but normally enough to get around in daytime.  As we
crossed the road onto a sidewalk, there was a line of bollards to
keep the French drivers on the road and safely off the sidewalk.
They were knee-high and the same color as the sidwalk.  He walked
right into one without seeing it.

He wasn't seriously hurt, but it was rather a shock.  Here's a worse one:

In Toronto (or maybe it was Scarborough; Toronto now, anyway) about
25 years ago, the rear doors on a bus malfunctioned, opening by
themselves and staying open.  Nobody fell out when it happened, and
a safety interlock immobilized the bus.

On a railroad crossing.

With a train coming.

I don't remember the casualty count, but it was a nasty crash.
(No, the bus driver wasn't at fault.  The crossing lights started
flashing just after the involuntary stop.  There wasn't time for
everyone to get off and away.)
--
