The ValuJet crash in Florida was caused by safety devices for another
type of airplane entirely, being shipped as cargo.  Interestingly
enough, no passenger life has ever been saved by these safety devices,
which are emergency oxygen supplies.

There's a guy named Perrow who wrote a book ages ago (it was
republished fairly recently) about how adding on all kinds of safety
system and back-up systems and stuff make systems so complex that
humans are unable to understand them.  The various systems interact in
ways that can't be predicted, leading to what he calls &quot;normal
accidents&quot;.  Other people have followed up this research, including a
group at Stanford (where I think Scott Sagan, Carl's son, is; he did a
fascinating study on nuclear weapons safety).

Mary &quot;Veteran of FMEA (Failure Mode Effects &amp; Analysis) sessions&quot;
